Final project --Chicago taxi project¶

1. Motivation¶

What's our dataset:

  • Our dataset contains: All taxi trip information for Chicago in 2023, including time, location, trip fee and so on. The data is from | City of Chicago | Data Portal (the size of dataset is 2.5GB). And weather data for Chicago throughout 2023, the url of which is https://www.wunderground.com/history/daily/us/il/chicago/KMDW.

Why did we choose these datasets:

  • We want to provide Chicago taxi drivers with guidance about Where and when are there the most potential passengers, how severe weather affects people's travel frequency and methods, and so on. Therefore, we have chosen a year's worth of taxi trip data and weather conditions for data analysis, aiming to give detailed advice for different situations, such as the impact of different months, Day of the Week, hours, etc., on taxi driver turnover.

What is our goal for the end user's experience:

  • We hope that the final visualization results are easy to understand and do their a favour, so that any Chicago taxi driver can use our website to guide them to find out what time, location, and weather conditions will help them pick up more passengers and earn more money.

2.1.1 Taxi dataset - Read and preprocessing¶

For taxi dataset, we firstly listed all the characteristics of the dataset. Based on our needs, we filtered out Trip Start Timestamp, Trip Seconds, Trip Miles, Fare, Pickup/Dropoff Community Area, their latitude and longitude.

According to the dataset description, we will have the missing value of the district which is out of the Chicago city. So we delete the rows which have the missing value.

What's more, we make the boxplot of fares when we want to explore the relationship between fares and district/ time. Finally, we drew bar charts for different time dimensions.

# Convert Date column to datetime format
df2['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df2['Date'])
df2.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# Define bad and worse weather conditions
bad_weather_conditions = ['Light Rain', 'Light Snow', 'Light Drizzle','Fog','Mist','Smoke','Light Rain with Thunder',
                          'Wintry Mix','Light Snow / Windy',
                          'Light Rain / Windy', 'Haze', 'T-Storm / Windy', 'Wintry Mix / Windy',
                          'Light Drizzle / Windy', 'Light Snow and Sleet',
                          'Light Sleet', 'Rain / Windy', 'Thunder / Windy', 
                          'Snow / Windy' ,'Patches of Fog']

worse_weather_conditions = ['Rain','Thunder',
                          'Heavy Rain', 'Heavy T-Storm / Windy', 
                          'Snow', 'Snow and Sleet', 'Thunder in the Vicinity', 
                          'Drizzle', 'Heavy Snow / Fog', 'Tornado', 'Heavy Snow / Windy',
                          'Heavy Snow / Windy / Fog',  'Heavy Rain / Windy', 'Light Snow with Thunder'] 

# Filter rows with bad and worse weather conditions
bad_weather_df2 = df2[df2['Condition'].isin(bad_weather_conditions)]
worse_weather_df2 = df2[df2['Condition'].isin(worse_weather_conditions)]

# Group by date and count the occurrences of bad and worse weather conditions
bad_weather_count_by_date = bad_weather_df2.groupby('Date').size()
worse_weather_count_by_date = worse_weather_df2.groupby('Date').size()

# Filter dates where the count is ten or more for bad weather
bad_weather_days = bad_weather_count_by_date[bad_weather_count_by_date >= 10].index.sort_values()

# Filter dates where the count is three or more for worse weather
worse_weather_days = worse_weather_count_by_date[worse_weather_count_by_date >= 3].index.sort_values()

# Filter dates where the count is ten or more for bad weather, excluding worse weather days
bad_weather_days = bad_weather_count_by_date[(bad_weather_count_by_date >= 10) & (~bad_weather_count_by_date.index.isin(worse_weather_days))].index.sort_values()

# Convert the index of bad_weather_count_by_date to a DataFrame
bad_weather_days_df2 = pd.DataFrame(bad_weather_days, columns=['Date'])
worse_weather_days_df2 = pd.DataFrame(worse_weather_days, columns=['Date'])

# Add a new column indicating bad weather
bad_weather_days_df2['weather'] = 'bad'
worse_weather_days_df2['weather'] = 'worse'
merged_df2 = pd.concat([bad_weather_days_df2, worse_weather_days_df2])

# Sort the merged DataFrame by date sequence
merged_df2_sorted = merged_df2.sort_values(by='Date')

# Reset index to make the first column numerical
merged_df2_sorted.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

# Create a DataFrame containing all dates of 2023
all_dates_2023 = pd.date_range(start='2023-01-01', end='2023-12-31', freq='D')
all_dates_df2 = pd.DataFrame({'Date': all_dates_2023})

# Merge the DataFrame containing all dates with the sorted merged DataFrame
merged_df2_complete = pd.merge(all_dates_df2, merged_df2_sorted, on='Date', how='left')

# Fill NaN values in the 'weather' column with 'normal'
merged_df2_complete['weather'].fillna('normal', inplace=True)

print(merged_df2_complete)

From the perspective of months, we observe that the highest number occurs in June. From this monthly perspective, we contemplate whether the severity of weather in different months affects the number of orders. Therefore, we attempt to analyze from a weather standpoint, seeking to identify potential correlations between weather conditions and ride volume.

From the perspective of days, we observe that Thursday has the highest number (with a significant decrease on weekends). However, we cannot derive much analysis solely from the days.

From the perspective of hours, we observe that the number of taxi rides is concentrated in the afternoon (with the fewest orders occurring between 1:00 AM and 5:00 AM). Additionally, analyzing from an hourly standpoint is highly valuable. We attempt to explore the passenger flow at different times in various areas to provide some guidance for taxi drivers.

                                             (~bad_weather_count_by_date.index.isin(worse_weather_count_by_date.index))]

# Convert the index of bad_weather_count_by_date to a DataFrame
bad_weather_days_df2 = pd.DataFrame({'Date': bad_weather_days.index, 'weather': 1})

# Filter dates where the count is three or more for worse weather
worse_weather_days = worse_weather_count_by_date[worse_weather_count_by_date >= 3]

# Convert the index of worse_weather_count_by_date to a DataFrame
worse_weather_days_df2 = pd.DataFrame({'Date': worse_weather_days.index, 'weather': 2})

# Merge the DataFrames
merged_df2 = pd.concat([bad_weather_days_df2, worse_weather_days_df2]).sort_values(by='Date')

# Create a DataFrame containing all dates of 2023
all_dates_2023 = pd.date_range(start='2023-01-01', end='2023-12-31')
all_dates_df2 = pd.DataFrame({'Date': all_dates_2023})

# Merge the DataFrame containing all dates with the sorted merged DataFrame
merged_df2_complete = pd.merge(all_dates_df2, merged_df2, on='Date', how='left')

# Fill NaN values in the 'weather' column with 'normal'
merged_df2_complete['weather'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

# Convert the 'Date' column to datetime format
merged_df2_complete['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(merged_df2_complete['Date'])

# Set the 'Date' column as the index
merged_df2_complete.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

precipitation = pd. Series (merged_df2_complete.weather)

# Set both index and column names to None
merged_df2_complete.index.name = None
merged_df2_complete.columns.name = None

# Plot the calmap

calmap.yearplot(merged_df2_complete, cmap='YlGnBu', linewidth=0.5, edgecolor='gray')

4. Genre¶

We opted for a magazine-style approach. It's the most direct, allowing users to access information easily without needing to learn how to use it. Additionally, this format effectively communicates our data analysis and is relatively simple, allowing us to focus more on data analysis.

4.1 Which tools did we use from each of the 3 categories of Visual Narrative:¶

Visual Narrative: We utilized a Consistent Visual Platform for Visual Structuring to enable users to freely and randomly browse the website. As the content is presented in parallel without any predefined chronological or hierarchical order.

We also employed Zooming for Highlighting, particularly in the section on the impact of time on order quantity, enlarging the charts representing the most significant factor, "hour of day", to guide users to pay more attention and explore further. There's no Transition Guidance as our web page remains within one scene without involving scene or visual transitions.

4.2 Which tools did we use from each of the 3 categories of Narrative Structure:¶

Narrative Structure: Our reading sequence is Random Access, allowing users to browse the website in any order they prefer. Our content without a specific chronological or hierarchical sequence, thus enabling users to independently choose the sections they are interested in browsing.

For Interactivity, we employed Hover Details, Selection tools, and Explicit Instruction. This allows users to hover over data charts to view detailed information and select specific time periods to see corresponding order quantities. As we've emphasized, we aim for the website's operations to be simple, straightforward, and "idiot-proof," hence providing clear guidance upfront.

For Messaging, we utilized Captions/Headlines to aid users in quickly understanding the content, Annotations to help users summarize information derived from charts, and introductory text at the beginning of the web page to introduce the main content, purpose, and simple usage instructions.

This is the plot about the variation of taxi trips data across time dimensions. We choose it because we can read many basic information from it.

The months with the highest order volume are June, May, and October, respectively. The months with the lowest order volume are January, February, and December. This may be due to the influence of temperature and season on people's willingness to travel.

Order volume is higher on weekdays compared to weekends. From Monday to Thursday, the number of orders shows an increasing trend, peaking on Thursday, and then starts to decline, reaching its lowest point on Sunday.

Order volume starts to significantly and steadily increase from 8 a.m.. Around 5 p.m., order volume peaks. After that, order volume rapidly decreases, reaching its lowest point around 3 a.m. in the early morning.

    Output('map-graph', 'figure'),
    [Input('hour-slider', 'value')]
)
def update_map(selected_hour):
    df['Trip Start Timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Trip Start Timestamp'], errors='coerce')

                           zoom=9,

                           labels={'Population': 'Population Count'})
    fig.update_layout(height=800, width=800)

  • During midnight hours, there is minimal activity in each area.
  • The peak commuting hours in the morning are from 5:00 to 8:00. The areas 8, 32, and 28 exhibit the highest passenger flow during this time. Subsequently, the passenger flow decreases rapidly in area 28, indicating the potential for more orders during peak commuting hours in these areas.
  • Most areas experience a continuous increase in passenger flow starting around 2-3 AM until around 4 PM, followed by a continuous decline until around 2-3 AM the next day. However, areas 6 and 56 seem to maintain their status from 7 AM to around 8 PM.
  • Areas with larger bases tend to have considerable passenger flow even during the early morning hours, often accompanied by more taxis. Therefore, choosing areas like 6 and 24 (with a significant proportion of passenger traffic during the early morning hours) can also be a good option.

5.5 The area with the highest number of large-miles trips.¶

In [ ]:
app2 = dash.Dash(__name__)

app2.layout = html.Div([
    dcc.Slider(
        id='hour-slider',
        min=0,
        max=23,
        value=12,
        marks={i: str(i) for i in range(24)},
        step=1,
    ),
    dcc.Graph(id='median-miles-graph')
])

@app2.callback(
    Output('median-miles-graph', 'figure'),
    Input('hour-slider', 'value')
)
def update_graph(selected_hour):
    # Filter the DataFrame for the selected hour
    filtered_df = df[df['Trip Start Timestamp'].dt.hour == selected_hour]

    # Calculate the median Trip Miles for each community area
    median_miles = filtered_df.groupby('Pickup Community Area')['Trip Miles'].median().reset_index()

    # Sort by median Trip Miles and select the top 14 areas
    top_areas = median_miles.sort_values(by='Trip Miles', ascending=False).head(14)

    # Create a new column combining the community area number and name
    top_areas['Community Info'] = top_areas['Pickup Community Area'].apply(
        lambda x: f"{x} - {community.get(x, 'Unknown')}"
    )

    # Create a line plot using the new column as x-axis labels
    fig = px.line(
        top_areas,
        x='Community Info',
        y='Trip Miles',
        line_shape='linear',  # Line shape: options are 'linear', 'spline', 'vhv', 'hvh', 'vh', 'hv'
        markers=True,  # Add markers
        labels={'Community Info': 'Community'}  # Customize axis labels
    )

    # Update the line style of the plot, changing the color to black
    fig.update_traces(line=dict(width=4, color="black"))

    # Add a yellow dashed line on the y-axis and label it "=15m"
    fig.add_shape(
        type='line',
        x0=0, x1=1,  # Range of the x-axis, represented in relative coordinates (0 for start, 1 for end)
        y0=15, y1=15,  # Position on the y-axis (fixed at 15 km)
        line=dict(
            color='#FFC700',
            width=2,  # Width of the dashed line
            dash='dash'  # 'dash' represents a dashed line
        ),
        xref='paper',  # Use 'paper' coordinate system (0~1)
        yref='y'  # Use the y-axis coordinates of the plot
    )

    # Add a new scatter plot, marking points where Trip Miles is greater than 15
    fig.add_scatter(
        x=top_areas[top_areas['Trip Miles'] > 15]['Community Info'],
        y=top_areas[top_areas['Trip Miles'] > 15]['Trip Miles'],
        mode='markers',
        marker=dict(size=10, color='#FFC700', symbol='circle'),  # Filled circle
        name='> 15 km'
    )

    return fig

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app2.run_server(mode='inline', port=8051,debug=True)

# Convert 'Trip Start Timestamp' to datetime

# Extract month
order_merged_df2['Month'] = order_merged_df2['Trip Start Timestamp'].dt.month

# Create 3x4 subplot grid
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 4, figsize=(10, 8))

# Initialize list to store all mean counts
all_monthly_means = []

weather_labels = ['normal weather', 'bad weather', 'worse weather']

# Iterate over each month
for month, ax in zip(range(1, 13), axes.flatten()):
    # Filter data for the current month
    monthly_data = order_merged_df2[order_merged_df2['Month'] == month]
    # Group by 'weather' and calculate mean of 'Counts'
    monthly_mean = monthly_data.groupby('weather')['Count'].mean()
    all_monthly_means.append(monthly_mean)
    # Plot the mean counts for each 'weather' condition
    bars = monthly_mean.plot(kind='bar', ax=ax, title=f'Month {month}', color='#0075FF', edgecolor='black', linewidth=2.5)
    # Remove grid lines
    ax.grid(False)

    # Set y-axis to display only tick marks and numerical labels
    ax.yaxis.set_ticks_position('left')
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', which='both', direction='out', length=5)  # Set tick marks to be outside

    # Set custom labels for the x-axis
    ax.set_xticks(range(len(weather_labels)))
    ax.set_xticklabels(weather_labels, rotation=45)

    # Set labels only on left column and bottom row
    if month % 4 != 1:  # Removes y-axis labels for all but the first column
        ax.set_yticklabels([])
    if month < 9:  # Removes x-axis labels for all but the bottom row
        ax.set_xticklabels([])
    ax.set_xlabel('')  # Remove x-axis labels
    ax.set_ylabel('')  # Remove y-axis labels

# Find the maximum and minimum values among all months
max_value = max([monthly_mean.max() for monthly_mean in all_monthly_means])
min_value = min([monthly_mean.min() for monthly_mean in all_monthly_means])

# Apply the maximum and minimum values to all subplots
for ax in axes.flatten():
    ax.set_ylim([min_value - 2000, max_value + 100])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Special weather conditions may potentially increase the number of orders. however, this pattern is not always consistent.

But at the same time, we believe that it might be more reasonable to explain this phenomenon by considering temperature. People may not have a strong desire to go out during the winter. Additionally, it's also possible that the harsh winter weather, such as heavy snowfall, makes it more difficult for people to accept.

6. Discussion¶

Smooth Progress:

  • We successfully identified the patterns of taxi order fluctuations in various areas of Chicago, as well as the areas with the highest number of orders.

  • We analyzed the most common commuting routes between areas, assisting drivers in planning their waiting routes more effectively.

  • We explored the areas with the highest median mileage during different time periods, indicating that drivers in these areas often have higher earnings potential.

  • Our data provides intuitive guidance and analysis for drivers comprehensively.

Improvement:

  • We lack data on the number of empty taxis in each area, making it difficult to calculate the ratio of taxi orders to empty taxis. This would provide better optimization and consider spatial-temporal allocation issues more effectively.

  • Regarding the impact of weather on order quantity, we only observed some trends but couldn't determine the exact influence. Therefore, further analysis on this aspect with stronger data support is needed.

  • Although we can analyze where the order volume is highest and provide driver recommendations, we didn't consider the information gap between passenger flow and taxi quantity in our analysis. In other words, a high order volume may also indicate greater competition among taxis.

  • If computational power and data allow, it would be beneficial to include data from 2022 and 2021. Analyzing only one year of data can lead to overfitting when analyzing seasonal variables, resulting in errors.

  • We used a magazine-style genre, which is straightforward and simple for presentation. However, it may reduce user initiative. In the future, we can work on enriching the interactivity of the website, such as adding buttons for playing animations.

  • The content we chose to display was derived from desktop research and brainstorming. However, this may not necessarily be the information that taxi drivers are most concerned about. Therefore, conducting surveys and usability tests in the future can help identify the information drivers are truly interested in and assess the rationality and user-friendliness of the website's interaction.
